{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music --> | name =Free Dirt Records | image = Free_Dirt_Records_shovel_logo,_2016.jpg | founded = {{start date|2006}} | founder = John Smith, Erica Haskell | distributor = [[AMPED Distribution]] (US)<ref>{{Cite web| title = Distribution| work = Free Dirt Records & Service Co.| accessdate = 2018-01-13| url = https://freedirt.net/pages/distribution}}</ref> | genre = [[Folk music|Folk]], [[roots rock|roots]], traditional | country = U.S. | location = Washington, DC | website = {{URL|www.freedirt.net}} }}
'''Free Dirt Records''' is a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-nominated<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=Joe |title=Grammys 2018: See the Complete List of Nominees |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/8047027/grammys-2018-complete-nominees-list |website=Billboard |accessdate=2 July 2018 |ref=Billboard}}</ref> [[independent record label]] founded in 2006 by John Smith and Erica Haskell that releases folk and [[Traditional music|roots]] music.<ref name="Village Voice">{{cite web|last1=Laban|first1=Linda|title=Free Dirt Records Showcase|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/event/free-dirt-records-showcase-8144998|website=The Village Voice|accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref>
==History== Free Dirt Records was founded while John Smith was working at [[Smithsonian Folkways]].<ref name="Kithfolk">{{cite web|last1=Leger|first1=Devon|title=Growing Up with Utah Phillips: Nevada City, Erica Haskell, and Utah’s West Coast Legacy|url=http://www.kithfolk.com/kithfolk-blog/2015/8/18/growing-up-with-utah-phillips|website=KITHFOLK|accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref> There he collaborated with an intern named Erica Haskell<ref name="Jackson Free Press">{{cite web|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Lacey|title=Erica Haskell|url=http://www.jacksonfreepress.com/news/2009/oct/08/erica-haskell/|website=Jackson Free Press|accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref> on a box set of spoken word recordings by singer and storyteller [[Utah Phillips]].<ref name="Kithfolk" /> After that project, Smith and Haskell decided to create a label where they could work with young artists making traditional music and showcase often overlooked material like spoken word. The label's first official release was by the traditional Bosnian group [[Mostar Sevdah Reunion]]. Since 2006, the label has released music by [[Pokey LaFarge]],<ref name="Riverfront Times">{{cite web|last1=Horn|first1=Nick|title=Pokey LaFarge on His Rounder Records Debut, Something in the Water|url=http://www.riverfronttimes.com/musicblog/2015/04/22/pokey-lafarge-on-his-rounder-records-debut-something-in-the-water|website=Riverfront Times|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref> Anna & Elizabeth,<ref name="Vice">{{cite web|last1=Adams|first1=Mason|title=LISTEN TO ANNA & ELIZABETH'S SPOOKY NEW TAKE ON AN OLD APPALACHIAN MURDER BALLAD|url=http://noisey.vice.com/blog/murder-ballad-stream|website=Vice|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref> [[Hackensaw Boys]], [[Julian Lage]] & [[Chris Eldridge]] (Grammy-nominated), Cahalen Morrison, [[Dori Freeman]],<ref name="Virginia Songbird">{{cite web|last1=Wicks|first1=Amanda|title=THE VIRGINIA SONGBIRD TAKES FLIGHT: A CONVERSATION WITH DORI FREEMAN|url=http://www.thebluegrasssituation.com/read/virginia-songbird-takes-flight-conversation-dori-freeman|website=The Bluegrass Situation|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref> and [[The Two Man Gentlemen Band]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Prescription Drugs (We're Having A Party!)|url=https://www.discogs.com/Two-Man-Gentlemen-Band-Prescription-Drugs-Were-Having-A-Party/release/3789305|website=Discogs|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref> Free Dirt also works with [[PM Press]] to co-release spoken word and folk music. Together they've put out lectures by [[Noam Chomsky]] and [[Howard Zinn]] and music from [[Chumbawamba]], [[Leon Rosselson]] and [[Robb Johnson]], among others. Free Dirt is based in [[Takoma, Washington, D.C.]]
